Cochise County School Superintendent
April 28 at 10:48 AM 路

Educational RESOURCES and Professional Development for teachers, students, and parents

The following link will take you to the University of Arizona and Thomas R. Brown Foundation's latest teacher resource newsletter. This issue lists free online resources prepared by the nation's most outstanding institutions, suitable for middle and high school Social Studies and Math teachers. They include resources for:
- Online summer p.d. workshops
- Using Covid 19 events to illustrate economic principles
- Teaching personal finance
- AP exam preparation
- Math resources for teachers, students, parents
- And more

Here's the link for details on each:
https://mailchi.mp/brownfoundations.org/ua-trbf-newsletter

post_text:
The Cochise County School Superintendent's Office and the Cochise Education Foundation regret to announce the indefinite postponement of the 2020 Teacher of the Year Banquet in order to observe and adhere to the recommendations of Federal, State and Health Officials.

Both the Superintendent's office, and the CEF are committed to the support and recognition of Cochise County's amazing educators, and we have been blown away by the efforts going on across the county to support and educate the county's children in this time of need.

We look forward to the opportunity to celebrate Cochise County educators and will announce a new date for the Banquet when circumstances allow.

We are "Connecting the Dots" by being a "Learning Community for Student Success."

Ladies and Gentlemen, we will announce our mini-grant winners on Friday, at the latest on Monday. Our Judges were busy reading, and tallying up the scores. We had 72 entries and will only be able to select 20 for the grants.
Our Judges were Gwen Calhoun, Ada Para and Christine Rodes. Our coordinator was Ben Reyna and a special thanks to our CEF secretary and Lowes Hardware for hosting this event. And last but not least SSVEC and our CEF President for supplying lunch.
We are BLESSED to have such amazing educators. Thank you for all that you do, We love you! ~Jacqui

post_text: Great Opportunity!
shared_text:
Superintendent Kathy Hoffman
June 4, 2019 at 11:00 AM 路

Know an outstanding student who's passionate about sharing the perspectives and experiences of his or her community? We want to hear their voice!

The Arizona Department of Education is seeking students to serve on its African American and Latinx Advisory Councils.

One student from a college/university and one student from a high school in Arizona will be chosen for each council. The Student Advisors will be selected by a subcommittee with representatives from the councils. The four students will serve from September 1, 2019, to July 2, 2020.

Learn more about these opportunities and apply here http://bit.ly/311wQp3.

The Cochise County Superintendents office is seeking proposals for workshops and presenters for the January 25  26th 2019 Innovations in Education Conference.

Share your expertise with Educators, parents, and community members. We invite you to consider topics in Technology, Behavioral health, Core/CTE Subjects, Special Education and interdisciplinary subjects to include art, music, classroom management workshops for our support staff and paraprofessionals.
We welcome your ideas even if it is not listed above.

Please contact Johanna Scott at (520) 432-8952 or Jhscott@cochise.az.gov; deadline is 30 October.

Help us to RECRUIT, RETAIN AND RECOGNIZE our teachers, consider becoming a school board member, we need you!

We need your voice, your knowledge, and your input. Consider becoming a school board member, information regarding the roles and responsibilities of school board members can be found at http://www.azsba.org/wp-content/uploads/2015/09/PC-School-Law-Session-5-Roles-and-Responsibilities.pdf .

Additional information regarding school boards can be found at the Arizona School Board Association (ASBA) website, http://azsba.org. Please do not hesitate to call the Cochise County Superintendent's office if you have any questions.

post_text:
It's a new year and it's time to look forward to the 2016 Teacher of the Year program coordinated by the Cochise County School Superintendent's office with assistance from the Cochise Education Foundation.

Each District Superintendent in Cochise County is emailed information and nomination packets. Cochise County School Districts are encouraged to submit one Teacher of the Year nominee application. (Due to the size of Douglas and Sierra Vista districts, they are allowed three nominees.) In addition, each school district is allowed to nominate one Education Special
Project for recognition.

The deadline for application submissions is February 5, 2016.

The annual banquet recognizing the teachers nominated and announcing the 2016 Teacher of the Year is scheduled for April 8 at the Thunder Mountain Activity Center on Fort Huachuca.

Would you or your organization like to help a teacher?

As previously posted, the Cochise Education Foundation has funded 21 mini-grants to Cochise County teachers for this school year. The Foundation actually received 103 applications which means that 82 of the requests remain unfunded.

If you or your club/organization would like to consider funding one of the remaining requests (in the amount of $200) please email wcrane@ssvec.com for a listing of the available projects.

The Cochise Education Foundation (CEF) is selling raffle tickets for a new 2015 Ford Mustang, 50th Anniversary Edition. Jim Click is donating the car, and tickets are $25 each or 5 for $100. All of the funds go directly to the Cochise Education Foundation which supports Cochise County teachers by providing mini-grants for the classroom and recognition at the Cochise County Teacher of the Year banquet.
